Machine Learning with
Data Streams
Unlock new insights and make predictions on-the-go. Join us as we explore
the world of Machine Learning with Data Streams.
by sh l
Introduction to Data Streams
What are Data
Streams?
Infinite, continuous and rapidly
changing flows of data. Unlike
traditional datasets, the data in data
streams may never repeat.
Use Cases
Data streams can be generated by
sensors, IoT devices, and social
media streams, and can be used in
applications like fraud detection,
recommendation systems and
network analysis.
Characteristics
High-volume, high-velocity, and
high-variety data with noise,
incompleteness and uncertainty. A
single pass over the data with limited
resources.
Challenges in Applying Traditional Machine Learning to
Data Streams
Concept Drift
Data concepts and distributions shift and
change over time, making models become out
of date. Solutions include online learning and
ensemble methods.
Speed and Resource Constraints
Traditional batch learning algorithms cannot
cope with the volume, velocity and variety of
data streams. Solutions include incremental
methods and resource-adaptive algorithms.
Labeling Complexity
Data labeling is typically manual and costly.
Solutions include active learning and semi-
supervised learning.
Algorithms for Machine Learning with Data
Streams
1
Naive Bayes
A probabilistic model that assumes
independence between the input features. It's
fast and memory-efficient, but accuracy may
2
Decision Trees
A tree-like model that classifies data using a
greedy, top-down procedure. It's easy to
interpret, but may be unstable and sensitive to
noise.
3
Random Forests
Ensemble of decision trees that aggregate their
predictions. It's robust and accurate, but may
be slow and hard to interpret.
4
Online Learning
Adaptive algorithms that update the model as
new data arrives. They can cope with speed
and concept drift, but may suffer from bias and
stability issues.
Concept Drift and How to Handle It
What is Concept Drift?
The constant evolution of data
distributions that lead to changes in
feature values, input space, and
target variable.
Types of Concept Drift
Covariate, feature, and target drift.
Understanding which type is
occurring underlies effective drift
handling and prevents model
degradation.
Drift Detection and
Adaptation Methods
Static versus dynamic detection, and
reactive versus proactive adaptation.
The choice of methods influences the
learning performance and resource
consumption.
Evaluation Methods for Data Stream Learning
Accuracy Metrics
Frequency-weighted accuracy and Kappa
statistics are commonly used to assess
model performance in data streams. Avoid
non-weighted accuracy as data sparsity
may affect its validity.
Window-Based Evaluation
Divide the data into time windows and
measure model performance in each
window. This method is simple and
flexible, but may not capture global
performance or handle concept drift well.
Online Evaluation
Incorporate predicted and actual data
pairs sequentially and incrementally. This
method avoids model reset, but may not
provide robust performance evaluation
under slow concept drift.
Applications of Machine Learning with Data
Streams
1Fraud Detection
Mining heterogeneous data streams from different
sources and detecting anomalous patterns in real-
time.
2
Recommendation Systems
Identifying customer preferences and behaviour
patterns, and making personalised suggestions in real-
time. 3Network Analysis
Learning complex network structures and detecting
critical events or malfunctioning nodes in real-time.
Conclusion and Future Directions
1Summary
Machine Learning with Data Streams is a challenging yet
fascinating field with great potential. Online learning,
ensemble methods, and drift detection and adaptation are
promising solutions to the challenges.
2Future Directions
Further research is needed on new algorithms that
combine advantages of both traditional batch learning and
data stream learning, on evaluation criteria that handle
concept drift, and on the ethical implications of data
stream learning.
